The Chrysler Payroll project is an example of a working object technolo,g project. We delivered the system in May 1997 with the second phase launch expected in January 1998. We expect the entire US payroll (120,000 employees) to be using the system by the year 2000. Nearly every aspect of its performance and capabilities has exceeded expectations. The practices that make this project work point out important considerations for managing advanced technology projects. This paper is an attempt to describe the nature of these successful practices, the organizational context in which they operate, and their interactions, which synergistically create an environment that is greater than the sum of its Parts-